        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h2>What is a prime number?</h2>
          <p>A prime number is a natural number greater than 1 that has no positive divisors other than 1 and itself. The first few primes are 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13... There are infinitely many primes — Euclid proved this over 2,000 years ago.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
          <details>
            <summary>Is 1 a prime number?</summary>
            <p>No. By definition, prime numbers must have exactly two distinct divisors — 1 and themselves. The number 1 only has one divisor, so it is neither prime nor composite.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Is 2 the only even prime?</summary>
            <p>Yes. Every even number greater than 2 is divisible by 2, so it cannot be prime. 2 is the only even prime number.</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What are prime numbers used for?</summary>
            <p>Prime numbers are fundamental to modern cryptography. The security of HTTPS, SSL and most internet encryption relies on the mathematical difficulty of factoring very large numbers into their prime factors.</p>
          </details>
